    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "You're right, I was just starting to describe the frontline defense! In an acute bacterial infection, the body deploys neutrophils like a highly organized, aggressive squad. These neutrophils are drawn to the site of infection through a process called **chemotaxis**, which is essentially them following chemical breadcrumbs released by the bacteria or damaged tissue.\n\nOnce they arrive, the action starts with **phagocytosis**, which is the literal \"eating\" of the bacteria. The neutrophil engulfs the microbe into a vesicle called a phagosome, and then fuses it with a lysosome containing potent antimicrobial enzymes and reactive oxygen species. This combination effectively destroys the invading bacteria, which is the body's immediate, brute-force solution to the sudden bacterial invasion.\n\nThis rapid, overwhelming deployment of neutrophils is why neutrophilia is so characteristic of acute bacterial sepsis or cellulitis. It's a swift, massive mobilization of the body's most immediate combat units.\n\n***\n\nNow, to bring this back to the *other* side of the coin—lymphocytosis—it's a much more strategic, slower engagement. Lymphocytes, unlike the immediate-action neutrophils, are the specialized intelligence agents. During a chronic viral infection, they are involved in",
