      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "The lymphocytes are the highly specialized, long-term tactical unit, which is a massive difference from the neutrophils' \"brute-force\" approach. Neutrophils are like a swarm of angry, indiscriminate fireflies, attacking anything that moves or looks like a threat in the immediate vicinity. Lymphocytes, however, are the highly trained, targeted assassins of the immune system.\n\nTheir ability to handle long-term threats stems from their adaptive immunity. They don't just randomly engulf things; they recognize specific molecular signatures, or antigens, on the pathogen. This recognition is incredibly precise, which is why they are so effective against viruses that replicate inside host cells.\n\nSpecifically, T-cells and B-cells handle this: B-cells produce antibodies that tag the specific pathogen for destruction, while T-cells directly identify and destroy the infected host cells—a level of surgical precision that the generalist neutrophil simply cannot achieve. This targeted, memory-based response is what allows the body to fight off chronic infections or remember a pathogen for future encounters.\n\n***\n\nThis is where the distinction is clearest for your USMLE: Neutrophils = Acute, Non-Specific Attack (Bacterial). Lymphocytes = Chronic, Specific Attack (Viral/",
